WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.924 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:01.924 --> 00:00:06.253 align:middle line:90%


00:00:06.253 --> 00:00:09.800 align:middle line:10%
>> It said that about
2,500 years ago,

00:00:09.800 --> 00:00:12.650 align:middle line:10%
the reformed ascetic
Siddhartha Gautama,

00:00:12.650 --> 00:00:16.940 align:middle line:10%
wishing to dispel all ignorance,
sat down under a sacred fig

00:00:16.940 --> 00:00:20.630 align:middle line:10%
tree to meditate with
final determination and was

00:00:20.630 --> 00:00:24.770 align:middle line:10%
enlightened to the
truth of all existence.

00:00:24.770 --> 00:00:26.630 align:middle line:84%
Over the next
millennium and a half,

00:00:26.630 --> 00:00:30.020 align:middle line:84%
the teachings of the Buddha
slowly spread throughout Asia,

00:00:30.020 --> 00:00:35.010 align:middle line:84%
bringing a light to darkness
and peace to conflict.

00:00:35.010 --> 00:00:38.600 align:middle line:84%
Now, the Dharma has come sailing
on the jet streams of modernity

00:00:38.600 --> 00:00:41.060 align:middle line:84%
into the heart of
this culture that

00:00:41.060 --> 00:00:45.320 align:middle line:84%
runs on the twin engines of
competition and acquisition,

00:00:45.320 --> 00:00:48.890 align:middle line:84%
where many consider cruelty to
be kindness and ignorance to be

00:00:48.890 --> 00:00:50.690 align:middle line:90%
knowledge.

00:00:50.690 --> 00:00:53.720 align:middle line:84%
If its history is any
judge, the subtle path

00:00:53.720 --> 00:00:57.110 align:middle line:84%
of spiritual development that
our colonialist forefathers

00:00:57.110 --> 00:01:00.920 align:middle line:84%
dubbed Buddhism has begun a
migration that, over time, will

00:01:00.920 --> 00:01:05.390 align:middle line:84%
leave it, and possibly modernity
itself, greatly transformed.

00:01:05.390 --> 00:01:06.790 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:01:06.790 --> 00:01:10.010 align:middle line:90%


00:01:10.010 --> 00:01:14.430 align:middle line:84%
>> What is it going
to look like from--

00:01:14.430 --> 00:01:15.570 align:middle line:90%
that's anyone's guess.

00:01:15.570 --> 00:01:17.190 align:middle line:90%
>> It will not survive.

00:01:17.190 --> 00:01:24.640 align:middle line:84%
It will be an anachronistic,
esoteric, Asiatic something

00:01:24.640 --> 00:01:25.440 align:middle line:90%
here in the West.

00:01:25.440 --> 00:01:28.620 align:middle line:84%
But nobody will take it serious
if it clings to old structures.

00:01:28.620 --> 00:01:31.500 align:middle line:84%
>> We're not going to create
an indigenous Western Buddhism.

00:01:31.500 --> 00:01:34.020 align:middle line:84%
And we don't want to create an
indigenous Western Buddhism.

00:01:34.020 --> 00:01:36.493 align:middle line:84%
We're not here to be, OK,
you guys were the Chinese

00:01:36.493 --> 00:01:38.160 align:middle line:84%
Buddhists.
[? You're the thing. ?] We're

00:01:38.160 --> 00:01:39.570 align:middle line:90%
American Buddhists.

00:01:39.570 --> 00:01:42.413 align:middle line:84%
Not at all, that's
useless, totally useless.

00:01:42.413 --> 00:01:43.830 align:middle line:84%
It's too late in
history for that.

00:01:43.830 --> 00:01:49.440 align:middle line:84%
>> If Buddhism is to become
a living and vital cultural

00:01:49.440 --> 00:01:54.600 align:middle line:84%
presence in modernity, it needs
to rethink some of its most

00:01:54.600 --> 00:01:55.890 align:middle line:90%
fundamental doctrines.

00:01:55.890 --> 00:01:58.920 align:middle line:84%
>> But I want to be
able to recognize it.

00:01:58.920 --> 00:02:00.600 align:middle line:90%
Do I call it psychology?

00:02:00.600 --> 00:02:02.700 align:middle line:90%
Do I call it stress reduction?

00:02:02.700 --> 00:02:05.430 align:middle line:90%
Do I call it art?

00:02:05.430 --> 00:02:07.770 align:middle line:84%
I want to be able to
recognize it as Buddhism.

00:02:07.770 --> 00:02:10.000 align:middle line:90%
So there, I'm old hat.

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:14.835 align:middle line:90%
Old traditionalist conservative.

00:02:14.835 --> 00:02:16.230 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:02:16.230 --> 00:02:18.090 align:middle line:90%


00:02:18.090 --> 00:02:21.750 align:middle line:84%
>> The societal imperative of
Buddhism has been described

00:02:21.750 --> 00:02:24.960 align:middle line:84%
as the battle between
enlightenment and ignorance one

00:02:24.960 --> 00:02:27.600 align:middle line:90%
individual at a time.

00:02:27.600 --> 00:02:30.120 align:middle line:84%
Modernity, then, would
be the battleground.

00:02:30.120 --> 00:02:33.780 align:middle line:84%
And how Buddhism responds
to its formidable challenges

00:02:33.780 --> 00:02:37.800 align:middle line:84%
will determine how
successful it will be.

00:02:37.800 --> 00:02:40.650 align:middle line:84%
So this is a road movie that
will wind through Europe

00:02:40.650 --> 00:02:44.100 align:middle line:84%
and North America to visit
many of the first generation

00:02:44.100 --> 00:02:48.120 align:middle line:84%
of Western-born Buddhist
teachers, the intrepid Dharma

00:02:48.120 --> 00:02:51.450 align:middle line:84%
pioneers, to look
through their eyes

00:02:51.450 --> 00:02:54.960 align:middle line:84%
at how the Buddha Dharma is
making out in its encounter

00:02:54.960 --> 00:02:55.820 align:middle line:90%
with the West.

00:02:55.820 --> 00:02:57.764 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:02:57.764 --> 00:03:08.470 align:middle line:90%


00:03:08.470 --> 00:03:10.810 align:middle line:84%
Like all world
religions, Buddhism

00:03:10.810 --> 00:03:14.440 align:middle line:84%
is no stranger to
migration into new lands.

00:03:14.440 --> 00:03:17.710 align:middle line:84%
What may be different, though,
is its chameleon-like ability

00:03:17.710 --> 00:03:20.952 align:middle line:84%
to adopt widely differing
cultural and religious forms.

00:03:20.952 --> 00:03:22.785 align:middle line:84%
>> You don't see that
in any other religion.

00:03:22.785 --> 00:03:23.585 align:middle line:90%
>> No.

00:03:23.585 --> 00:03:25.950 align:middle line:84%
I think there's a
fundamental reason for that.

00:03:25.950 --> 00:03:28.690 align:middle line:84%
>> John Crook is the
principal Dharma teacher

00:03:28.690 --> 00:03:31.640 align:middle line:84%
in England's Western
Chan Fellowship.

00:03:31.640 --> 00:03:33.490 align:middle line:84%
He lives in the
west of the country

00:03:33.490 --> 00:03:36.820 align:middle line:84%
off a dirt road in a
large old house that also

00:03:36.820 --> 00:03:38.980 align:middle line:90%
serves for individual retreats.

00:03:38.980 --> 00:03:45.150 align:middle line:84%
>> The initial prophets of,
say, of Islam or of Christianity

00:03:45.150 --> 00:03:48.160 align:middle line:84%
were very great
men, very clearly.

00:03:48.160 --> 00:03:50.230 align:middle line:84%
But what happened in
both cases after that,

00:03:50.230 --> 00:03:53.800 align:middle line:84%
the formation of churches,
all depended upon dogmas.

00:03:53.800 --> 00:03:57.070 align:middle line:84%
Things must be
believed or things must

00:03:57.070 --> 00:03:59.420 align:middle line:90%
be behaved in certain ways.

00:03:59.420 --> 00:04:01.570 align:middle line:84%
And in both Christianity
and in Islam,

00:04:01.570 --> 00:04:06.580 align:middle line:84%
this has led to terrible warfare
and disputes between Catholic

00:04:06.580 --> 00:04:09.070 align:middle line:84%
and Protestant and between
the branches of Islam--

00:04:09.070 --> 00:04:09.870 align:middle line:90%
appalling.

00:04:09.870 --> 00:04:12.070 align:middle line:90%
You can see the sea out there.

00:04:12.070 --> 00:04:14.680 align:middle line:84%
By and large, Buddhism
has been free from that.

00:04:14.680 --> 00:04:16.120 align:middle line:90%
Why is that?

00:04:16.120 --> 00:04:20.560 align:middle line:84%
Because, in my view, it's
dependent not on dogmas

00:04:20.560 --> 00:04:24.400 align:middle line:84%
but on what are, in fact,
empirical statements about how

00:04:24.400 --> 00:04:25.860 align:middle line:90%
the mind works.

00:04:25.860 --> 00:04:27.270 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:04:27.270 --> 00:04:30.090 align:middle line:90%


00:04:30.090 --> 00:04:33.800 align:middle line:84%
>> San Francisco is Buddhism's
birthplace in the West

00:04:33.800 --> 00:04:35.660 align:middle line:90%
in modern times.

00:04:35.660 --> 00:04:38.360 align:middle line:84%
It had previously arrived
here in the early years

00:04:38.360 --> 00:04:42.800 align:middle line:84%
of the 19th century with
Chinese and Japanese immigrants.

00:04:42.800 --> 00:04:45.920 align:middle line:84%
But it remained within
their communities.

00:04:45.920 --> 00:04:48.260 align:middle line:84%
In the succeeding
decades, here and there,

00:04:48.260 --> 00:04:50.450 align:middle line:84%
small pockets of
Western converts

00:04:50.450 --> 00:04:53.210 align:middle line:84%
gathered around
an Asian teacher.

00:04:53.210 --> 00:04:56.450 align:middle line:84%
But it wasn't until the
counterculture of the 1950s

00:04:56.450 --> 00:04:59.600 align:middle line:84%
and '60s that the ground
was fertile enough

00:04:59.600 --> 00:05:01.790 align:middle line:84%
to sustain a
permanent transplant.

00:05:01.790 --> 00:05:04.480 align:middle line:90%


00:05:04.480 --> 00:05:07.690 align:middle line:84%
By the late '50s, the leading
lights of the Beat Generation

00:05:07.690 --> 00:05:10.900 align:middle line:84%
had congregated here,
many of them inspired

00:05:10.900 --> 00:05:14.193 align:middle line:90%
by the ideas of Zen Buddhism.

00:05:14.193 --> 00:05:15.860 align:middle line:84%
>> Nothing was really
practiced, was it?

00:05:15.860 --> 00:05:18.460 align:middle line:84%
>> Actually, not
many people, no.

00:05:18.460 --> 00:05:20.680 align:middle line:84%
There was no such
thing as practice.

00:05:20.680 --> 00:05:24.520 align:middle line:84%
Gary Schneider went
to Japan and practiced

00:05:24.520 --> 00:05:28.585 align:middle line:84%
in [? Rinzei ?] Monastery, and
probably a few other people.

00:05:28.585 --> 00:05:32.380 align:middle line:84%
>> Mel Weitzman is the Roshi
at the Berkeley Zen Center.

00:05:32.380 --> 00:05:34.960 align:middle line:84%
Now in his 80s,
in the late '50s,

00:05:34.960 --> 00:05:38.080 align:middle line:84%
he was an art student plugged
into the counterculture scene.

00:05:38.080 --> 00:05:40.193 align:middle line:90%
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:05:40.193 --> 00:05:41.110 align:middle line:90%
>> There was interest.

00:05:41.110 --> 00:05:43.840 align:middle line:84%
But the interest didn't
have any place to go.

00:05:43.840 --> 00:05:47.110 align:middle line:84%
So when Suzuki Roshi came, he
was one of the first people--

00:05:47.110 --> 00:05:48.620 align:middle line:90%
maybe the first one, really--

00:05:48.620 --> 00:05:50.795 align:middle line:90%
'59.

00:05:50.795 --> 00:05:56.050 align:middle line:84%
>> In 1959, a Zen priest named
Shunryu Suzuki had arrived from

00:05:56.050 --> 00:05:59.740 align:middle line:84%
Japan to minister to San
Francisco's immigrant Japanese

00:05:59.740 --> 00:06:01.240 align:middle line:90%
community.

00:06:01.240 --> 00:06:05.230 align:middle line:84%
But he also found interest from
an unexpected source thanks

00:06:05.230 --> 00:06:06.165 align:middle line:90%
to the phone company.

00:06:06.165 --> 00:06:08.500 align:middle line:90%
>> Here we are.

00:06:08.500 --> 00:06:10.765 align:middle line:84%
People started calling
him because they

00:06:10.765 --> 00:06:14.250 align:middle line:90%
saw Zen in the telephone book.

00:06:14.250 --> 00:06:16.660 align:middle line:84%
And they were looking
for something.

00:06:16.660 --> 00:06:21.480 align:middle line:84%
Then he said, well, I start
sitting at 5:45 in the morning.

00:06:21.480 --> 00:06:23.260 align:middle line:84%
So you're welcome to
come and sit with me.

00:06:23.260 --> 00:06:24.130 align:middle line:90%
And people did.

00:06:24.130 --> 00:06:27.190 align:middle line:84%
We have about eight
residents here.

00:06:27.190 --> 00:06:30.220 align:middle line:84%
And then, finally, the
Japanese congregation

00:06:30.220 --> 00:06:35.080 align:middle line:90%
gave them a room upstairs.

00:06:35.080 --> 00:06:38.350 align:middle line:84%
This is where Dokusan
would do interviews.

00:06:38.350 --> 00:06:41.140 align:middle line:84%
So little by little,
the Zen Center

00:06:41.140 --> 00:06:43.212 align:middle line:90%
formed around Suzuki Roshi.

00:06:43.212 --> 00:06:44.170 align:middle line:90%
You want to see inside?

00:06:44.170 --> 00:06:45.466 align:middle line:90%
>> Sure.

00:06:45.466 --> 00:06:47.590 align:middle line:84%
>> I have to separate
my keys from--

00:06:47.590 --> 00:06:50.386 align:middle line:90%


00:06:50.386 --> 00:06:51.830 align:middle line:90%
>> Ooh, very serious.

00:06:51.830 --> 00:06:53.046 align:middle line:90%
[CHUCKLES]

00:06:53.046 --> 00:06:57.110 align:middle line:84%
>> And then, there was always
a tension between the Japanese

00:06:57.110 --> 00:06:59.305 align:middle line:84%
congregation and the
American congregation.

00:06:59.305 --> 00:07:00.680 align:middle line:84%
Because the American
congregation

00:07:00.680 --> 00:07:02.080 align:middle line:90%
was a lot of hippies.

00:07:02.080 --> 00:07:03.680 align:middle line:84%
Not everybody-- I
mean, there were

00:07:03.680 --> 00:07:06.570 align:middle line:84%
doctors and lawyers,
professional people,

00:07:06.570 --> 00:07:11.600 align:middle line:90%
but a good deal of hippiness.

00:07:11.600 --> 00:07:14.600 align:middle line:84%
And Suzuki Roshi
loved the hippies

00:07:14.600 --> 00:07:19.070 align:middle line:84%
because they
represented something

00:07:19.070 --> 00:07:22.490 align:middle line:84%
that people were actually
seeking seriously.

00:07:22.490 --> 00:07:26.560 align:middle line:84%
Because the Japanese
congregation was like a church.

00:07:26.560 --> 00:07:32.010 align:middle line:84%
So he was really taken by
the innocence of the hippies.

00:07:32.010 --> 00:07:33.170 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:07:33.170 --> 00:07:33.970 align:middle line:90%


00:07:33.970 --> 00:07:37.290 align:middle line:84%
>> The young denizens of the
counter-culture soon received

00:07:37.290 --> 00:07:41.590 align:middle line:84%
Suzuki Roshi's
full-time attention.

00:07:41.590 --> 00:07:44.980 align:middle line:84%
He had Mel Weitzman looking
for property in Berkeley

00:07:44.980 --> 00:07:47.950 align:middle line:84%
while others found an old
home for single Jewish women

00:07:47.950 --> 00:07:53.950 align:middle line:84%
in the city proper that became
the San Francisco Zen Center.

00:07:53.950 --> 00:07:56.760 align:middle line:84%
There was, however, at
least one cultural ritual

00:07:56.760 --> 00:07:59.740 align:middle line:84%
of the hippies that was
incompatible with Zen

00:07:59.740 --> 00:08:00.947 align:middle line:90%
meditation.

00:08:00.947 --> 00:08:02.408 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:08:02.408 --> 00:08:04.843 align:middle line:90%


00:08:04.843 --> 00:08:08.920 align:middle line:84%
>> It was not at all unusual
in the beginning for one day

00:08:08.920 --> 00:08:11.420 align:middle line:84%
sitting to end and for a bunch
of people to go out to Golden

00:08:11.420 --> 00:08:14.430 align:middle line:90%
Gate Park and get stoned.

00:08:14.430 --> 00:08:18.020 align:middle line:90%
It changed with time.

00:08:18.020 --> 00:08:21.150 align:middle line:84%
It's hard to sit
[INAUDIBLE] stoned, really.

00:08:21.150 --> 00:08:22.727 align:middle line:90%
It doesn't work very well.

00:08:22.727 --> 00:08:24.038 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:08:24.038 --> 00:08:24.912 align:middle line:90%


00:08:24.912 --> 00:08:28.500 align:middle line:84%
>> Despite these early hiccups,
it was clear that conditions

00:08:28.500 --> 00:08:33.049 align:middle line:84%
were now ripe for the
Dharma to rise in the West.

00:08:33.049 --> 00:08:36.799 align:middle line:84%
Soon, other Zen teachers were
sailing for Western shores.

00:08:36.799 --> 00:08:41.659 align:middle line:84%
Bernie Glassman, Roshi's teacher
Maezumi Roshi in Los Angeles,

00:08:41.659 --> 00:08:45.770 align:middle line:84%
and in Paris, [INAUDIBLE]
master Taisen Deshimaru

00:08:45.770 --> 00:08:49.088 align:middle line:90%
were just a few of many.

00:08:49.088 --> 00:08:53.120 align:middle line:84%
and Westerners were also taking
advantage of the new jet travel

00:08:53.120 --> 00:08:57.500 align:middle line:84%
to head off to the East, finding
teachers in Japan, Thailand,

00:08:57.500 --> 00:08:59.630 align:middle line:90%
Burma, and Ceylon.

00:08:59.630 --> 00:09:04.730 align:middle line:84%
And as a result of the tragedy
of the Tibetan exodus of 1959,

00:09:04.730 --> 00:09:07.730 align:middle line:84%
to India and Nepal where
the Dalai Lama and many

00:09:07.730 --> 00:09:10.250 align:middle line:84%
of the great
Tibetan masters were

00:09:10.250 --> 00:09:14.073 align:middle line:84%
accessible to the outside
world for the very first time.

00:09:14.073 --> 00:09:15.925 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:09:15.925 --> 00:09:19.640 align:middle line:90%


00:09:19.640 --> 00:09:23.630 align:middle line:84%
By the late '60s and early
'70s, the Western-born acolytes

00:09:23.630 --> 00:09:27.260 align:middle line:84%
were beginning to return home
to face the challenge of how

00:09:27.260 --> 00:09:29.900 align:middle line:84%
to teach the Buddha
Dharma in a culture

00:09:29.900 --> 00:09:33.305 align:middle line:84%
so radically different
from its Asian roots.

00:09:33.305 --> 00:09:36.090 align:middle line:84%
>> The rise of modern
technology, transportation,

00:09:36.090 --> 00:09:36.920 align:middle line:90%
communication.

00:09:36.920 --> 00:09:40.880 align:middle line:84%
This whole society is
radically unlike any society

00:09:40.880 --> 00:09:43.940 align:middle line:84%
that Buddhism has
gravitated to or migrated to

00:09:43.940 --> 00:09:47.352 align:middle line:84%
and then assimilated with
over the last 2,500 years.

00:09:47.352 --> 00:09:48.935 align:middle line:84%
So this is an
unprecedented challenge.

00:09:48.935 --> 00:09:50.138 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:09:50.138 --> 00:09:51.026 align:middle line:90%


00:09:51.026 --> 00:09:53.930 align:middle line:84%
>> The challenge has
begun to take shape.

00:09:53.930 --> 00:09:56.060 align:middle line:84%
There are the usual
scandals that plague

00:09:56.060 --> 00:09:58.370 align:middle line:90%
those in spiritual authority.

00:09:58.370 --> 00:10:01.846 align:middle line:84%
>> The different women
didn't know about each other.

00:10:01.846 --> 00:10:05.000 align:middle line:84%
>> And there were profound
debates raging in a quietly

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:08.330 align:middle line:84%
Buddhist way about the role
of the spiritual teacher.

00:10:08.330 --> 00:10:12.350 align:middle line:84%
>> You are in a marketplace
situation that is driven more

00:10:12.350 --> 00:10:16.850 align:middle line:84%
by desire for fame and money
and success in a very worldly

00:10:16.850 --> 00:10:17.750 align:middle line:90%
sense.

00:10:17.750 --> 00:10:20.990 align:middle line:84%
>> The suitability of
Asian cultural forms--

00:10:20.990 --> 00:10:24.440 align:middle line:84%
>> We decided it was fine
for people to sit in chairs

00:10:24.440 --> 00:10:26.330 align:middle line:84%
because that's what
we do in this culture.

00:10:26.330 --> 00:10:29.575 align:middle line:84%
People didn't have to wear
robes or special garments.

00:10:29.575 --> 00:10:33.770 align:middle line:84%
>> The place of monasticism
in a culture of decidedly lay

00:10:33.770 --> 00:10:35.245 align:middle line:90%
practitioners--

00:10:35.245 --> 00:10:38.600 align:middle line:84%
>> Westerners think that
monasticism is something

00:10:38.600 --> 00:10:42.410 align:middle line:84%
Catholics did and we Protestants
don't, even if they happen

00:10:42.410 --> 00:10:43.790 align:middle line:90%
to be Jewish.

00:10:43.790 --> 00:10:46.190 align:middle line:84%
>> And even the fundamental
question of, what is

00:10:46.190 --> 00:10:48.860 align:middle line:90%
the essence of Buddhism itself?

00:10:48.860 --> 00:10:52.310 align:middle line:84%
Though many Buddhists might
disagree on the fine print,

00:10:52.310 --> 00:10:54.290 align:middle line:84%
most would agree
that the essence

00:10:54.290 --> 00:10:57.260 align:middle line:84%
can be found in the first
teachings of the Buddha.

00:10:57.260 --> 00:11:00.350 align:middle line:84%
>> If you look at the
history of Buddhism,

00:11:00.350 --> 00:11:06.500 align:middle line:84%
it is always of fine
adjustments and changes in those

00:11:06.500 --> 00:11:09.260 align:middle line:84%
fundamental, what are sometimes
called the fundamental

00:11:09.260 --> 00:11:12.420 align:middle line:90%
formulae, of the Buddha.

00:11:12.420 --> 00:11:13.220 align:middle line:90%
So what are they?

00:11:13.220 --> 00:11:15.210 align:middle line:84%
Well, of course, it's
the law of co-dependent

00:11:15.210 --> 00:11:22.020 align:middle line:84%
arising as the root of
the Four Noble Truths.

00:11:22.020 --> 00:11:26.090 align:middle line:84%
>> The Four Noble Truths explain
the nature of the suffering

00:11:26.090 --> 00:11:28.070 align:middle line:90%
and dissatisfaction--

00:11:28.070 --> 00:11:31.520 align:middle line:84%
its cause, its end, and
the path of practice that

00:11:31.520 --> 00:11:33.590 align:middle line:90%
leads to its end.

00:11:33.590 --> 00:11:37.580 align:middle line:84%
The law of co-dependent
arising is their foundation.

00:11:37.580 --> 00:11:41.180 align:middle line:84%
It states that all things arise
from an infinite web of cause

00:11:41.180 --> 00:11:42.480 align:middle line:90%
and effect.

00:11:42.480 --> 00:11:46.010 align:middle line:84%
And so no thing
exists independently.

00:11:46.010 --> 00:11:51.140 align:middle line:84%
Everything is void or empty
of an inherent self nature.

00:11:51.140 --> 00:11:55.430 align:middle line:84%
The implications of this are
as subtle as they are profound.

00:11:55.430 --> 00:11:57.470 align:middle line:10%
And this has made the
role of the teacher

00:11:57.470 --> 00:11:59.570 align:middle line:10%
essential for their
full unfolding

00:11:59.570 --> 00:12:02.220 align:middle line:10%
within the mind of the student.

00:12:02.220 --> 00:12:07.010 align:middle line:84%
But in today's West, that
role is facing new challenges.

00:12:07.010 --> 00:12:09.560 align:middle line:84%
We begin in the Bay
Area with its largest

00:12:09.560 --> 00:12:12.920 align:middle line:84%
Buddhist institution, the
fruit of Suzuki Roshi's

00:12:12.920 --> 00:12:16.956 align:middle line:84%
pioneering efforts, the
San Francisco Zen Center.

